<doc id="147939" wikidata="Q1355804" url="?curid=147939" title="Constant of integration">
<text>In calculus, the constant of integration, often denoted by formula_1 (or formula_2), is a constant term added to an antiderivative of a function formula_3 to indicate that the indefinite integral of formula_3 (i.e., the set of all antiderivatives of formula_3), on a connected domain, is only defined up to an additive constant. This constant expresses an ambiguity inherent in the construction of antiderivatives.

More specifically, if a function formula_3 is defined on an interval, and formula_7 is an antiderivative of formula_8 then the set of &quot;all&quot; antiderivatives of formula_3 is given by the functions formula_10 where formula_1 is an arbitrary constant (meaning that &quot;any&quot; value of formula_1 would make formula_13 a valid antiderivative). For that reason, the indefinite integral is often written as formula_14 although the constant of integration might be sometimes omitted in lists of integrals for simplicity.

==Origin==

The derivative of any constant function is zero. Once one has found one antiderivative formula_7 for a function formula_8 adding or subtracting any constant formula_1 will give us another antiderivative, because formula_18 The constant is a way of expressing that every function with at least one antiderivative will have an infinite number of them.

Let formula_19 and formula_20 be two everywhere differentiable functions. Suppose that formula_21 for every real number &quot;x&quot;. Then there exists a real number formula_1 such that formula_23 for every real number &quot;x&quot;.

To prove this, notice that formula_24 So formula_25 can be replaced by formula_26 and formula_27 by the constant function formula_28 making the goal to prove that an everywhere differentiable function whose derivative is always zero must be constant:

Choose a real number formula_29 and let formula_30 For any &quot;x&quot;, the fundamental theorem of calculus, together with the assumption that the derivative of formula_25 vanishes, implying that 

formula_32

thereby showing that formula_25 is a constant function.

Two facts are crucial in this proof. First, the real line is connected. If the real line were not connected, one would not always be able to integrate from our fixed &quot;a&quot; to any given &quot;x&quot;. For example, if one were to ask for functions defined on the union of intervals [0,1] and [2,3], and if &quot;a&quot; were 0, then it would not be possible to integrate from 0 to 3, because the function is not defined between 1 and 2. Here, there will be &quot;two&quot; constants, one for each connected component of the domain. In general, by replacing constants with locally constant functions, one can extend this theorem to disconnected domains. For example, there are two constants of integration for formula_34, and infinitely many for formula_35, so for example, the general form for the integral of 1/&quot;x&quot; is:

formula_36

Second, formula_25 and formula_27 were assumed to be everywhere differentiable. If formula_25 and formula_27 are not differentiable at even one point, then the theorem might fail. As an example, let formula_7 be the Heaviside step function, which is zero for negative values of &quot;x&quot; and one for non-negative values of &quot;x&quot;, and let formula_42 Then the derivative of formula_25 is zero where it is defined, and the derivative of formula_27 is always zero. Yet it&#x27;s clear that formula_25 and formula_27 do not differ by a constant, even if it is assumed that formula_25 and formula_27 are everywhere continuous and almost everywhere differentiable the theorem still fails. As an example, take formula_25 to be the Cantor function and again let formula_50

It turns out that adding and subtracting constants is the only flexibility available in finding different antiderivatives of the same function. That is, all antiderivatives are the same up to a constant. To express this fact for formula_51 one can write:
formula_52
where formula_1 is constant of integration. It is easily determined that all of the following functions are antiderivatives of formula_54:
formula_55

==Significance==

The inclusion of the constant of integration is necessitated in some, but not all circumstances. For instance, when evaluating definite integrals using the fundamental theorem of calculus, the constant of integration can be ignored as it will always cancel with itself.

However, different methods of computation of indefinite integrals can result in multiple resulting antiderivatives, each implicitly containing different constants of integration, and no particular option may be considered simplest. For example, formula_56 can be integrated in at least three different ways.

formula_57Additionally, omission of the constant, or setting it to zero, may make it prohibitive to deal with a number of problems, such as those with initial value conditions. A general solution containing the arbitrary constant is often necessary to identify the correct particular solution. For example, to obtain the antiderivative of formula_54 that has the value 400 at &quot;x&quot; = π, then only one value of formula_1 will work (in this case formula_60).

The constant of integration also implicitly or explicitly appears in the language of differential equations. Almost all differential equations will have many solutions, and each constant represents the unique solution of a well-posed initial value problem.

An additional justification comes from abstract algebra. The space of all (suitable) real-valued functions on the real numbers is a vector space, and the differential operator formula_61 is a linear operator. The operator formula_61 maps a function to zero if and only if that function is constant. Consequently, the kernel of formula_61 is the space of all constant functions. The process of indefinite integration amounts to finding a pre-image of a given function. There is no canonical pre-image for a given function, but the set of all such pre-images forms a coset. Choosing a constant is the same as choosing an element of the coset. In this context, solving an initial value problem is interpreted as lying in the hyperplane given by the initial conditions.

